I wish I was blown away by Gary Danko, I really do. My company hosted a dinner here and I'm not usually one for uptight upscale restaurants but in the holiday spirit I was up for it, and plus if it's on the company tab why not? They saved us a room upstairs. It was intimate and the room smelled lovely. The fresh flowers were a romantic touch. We each chose the three course option. I opted for the rock shrimp risotto, the lobster, and the filet. They start out by giving you slivers of bread and butter. If I could eat one thing forever it would be bread and butter and it's always been my weakness. For Valentine's Day I think it's much more romantic and practical to get your lover a loaf of quality bread than flowers that she could never eat. The bread here is tasty! And the servers are like AI robots and understand when your plate is empty and they keep comin with their yield and oh is it fruitful. The evening started off with a small bowl of mushroom soup, or what I prefer to it as mushroom essence. The portion was made for ants. The rock shrimp risotto was how I would imagine it to be--creamy and filling but somehow a tad delicate with the lightly crunchy rock shrimp bits. This by itself was filling on its own and whatever dairy they put in really made me bloated. Delicious nonetheless! The rockstar highlight of my night was probably their lobster dish. I don't eat lobster often because I prefer the flavor of crab but this lobster was buttery, soft yet had undertones of crunchiness, and was just decadent. I could eat ten plates of this if they let me and if my cholesterol would be kind to me. The star of the show was supposed to be the filet with the blue cheese, however I was underwhelmed as this was said to be one of their more popular dishes. I'm a fan of steak and think it's a good baseline dish to compare restaurants however this one was my least favorite. The steak didn't have a steak like flavor but was instead masked by the strong aroma and presence of an sweltering deep onion base. The whole night I was burping pure sweated onion flavor. I think I could have done without the sauce at the bottom and just ate the steak dry with the potato bits. For such a quality cut of meat I felt like it was ruined by the overwhelming scent of onion that it felt as though I ate onion flesh. You technically don't have to order dessert as they bring out mini bite sized pieces of fun at the end. The lobster was definitely the highlight. The customer service was good in the fact that they were attentive and each waiter came out in line order as if they were marching to set your plate. They could crack a smile lol but I guess that's the appeal of a serious place like this. Overall I would say the food was not memorable enough for me or didn't feel special as I thought it would.

Gary Danko is one of two restaurants I have been to in my life that creates an experience that is worth the money, with Bacchanalia in Atlanta being the other. First, this dinner shouldn't have happened. I had called several months in advance to try and get a reservation for the week of Thanksgiving 2019. There was nothing. On a chance, and knowing how much I wanted to dine there, my husband called when we arrived in San Francisco and got a reservation! I was so excited. Everything was superb. Typically when I do a review, I look at decor, waitstaff, presentation, food, and timelessness. Everything is what you would expect from the Michelin rated and James Beard award-winning restaurant. What stood out as the highlight of our experience was the sommelier that educated us on the wine pairings accompanying our five-course price-fixed meal. The sommelier introduced each wine that would be complementing each course of our meal. He was not only knowledgable on an expert level; he took the time to answer our questions, helping us truly appreciate the reasoning behind each selection. This in turn, elevated our overall dining experience. Our teenaged daughter decided to stay at the hotel. We had encouraged her to join us, but she was exhausted from our day of sightseeing. We had made small talk with our head waiter, and at the end of our meal, we were not only treated so a delicious sampling of small sweets, but the head waiter had also prepared one to take back to our daughter! It was a multitude of little things like this gesture, making this experience a once in a lifetime memory for me.

I started off the new year by dining at one Michelin star restaurant. My boyfriend and I decided to go with the 5 course meal because we haven't eaten much since lunch time. We said that if we were still hungry after our 5 courses, we would walk over to In-n-Out for more food haha. Once we got to the restaurant, the hostess asked if we wanted to coat check our jackets. Within a few minutes, we were quickly seated to our table. One of the staff gave me a table bag hook to hang my bag. This is actually a really genius idea! I have this item at home too, but I forgot to bring it. We were given the drink and food menus as well as tap water and a complimentary small sweet carrot soup (?). I couldn't remember what our waitress said that the soup was, but it was delicious. We were also served complimentary bread and butter. WARNING: DO NOT FILL UP ON BREAD. This is a dangerous idea! I always tell myself not to eat too much bread even though I love bread. I can tell you that eating 3 slices of bread was definitely a bad idea for me! FOOD: *Risotto with Rock Shrimp, Dungeness Crab, Celery Root and White Beech Mushrooms (5/5) - Top 2 favorite. I love rice and cheese. This dish didn't feel too heavy. The crab was definitely a nice touch to this dish! *Seared Striped Bass with Petite Thai Salad, Broccoli Rabe and Satay Sauce (3.5/5) - I enjoyed the seared bass, but I wasn't too fund of the salad. I don't like minced veggies as much. The flavor was just okay. *Lemon Pepper Duck Breast with Duck Hash, Celeriac-Garlic Purée, Belgain Endive and Cardamom Poached Pears (5/5) - I really enjoyed the duck breast and duck hash. I've never had duck hash before, so this was very interesting to try. *Pork Tenderloin with Confit Pork Belly, Brussels Sprouts, Chestnuts, Butternut Squash, Apples and Raisin-Pine Nut Relish (5/5) - Top 2 favorite. This dish had a good balance of meat and delicious veggies. *Grand Marnier Soufflé with Orange Sauce and Blood Orange Sorbet (4/5) - I really enjoyed the souffle, but the orange sauce was WAY TOO SWEET. If you compare this to milk tea, I would say that the sugar level is like at least 200%! I couldn't eat the orange sauce anymore, so I just finished the souffle and the sorbet instead. Towards the end of our 5 courses, we were given a plate of small bite size desserts to eat with our main desserts as well. We were also given complimentary breakfast treats! SERVICE (5/5): The staff was friendly, professional, and very attentive! We were constantly getting water refills and bread refills. Whenever we finished a course, the staff would quickly clear our table and provide us with a new pair of silverware. We were constantly being asked if the food was okay. Whenever we stepped away from our seat to use the restroom, the staff would fold our handkerchiefs and place it back on the table. Once you're done eating and paying for your food, they will ask if you had your car valeted or if you want them to call a taxi to get you a ride home. Very excellent service! OVERALL EXPERIENCE: We had a wonderful dining experience here. The food was good, but it wasn't as spectacular/hyped as I thought it would be. IMO, there are non-Michelin star restaurants that have more amazing food than this restaurant. I must say, we definitely misjudged out appetites. After our 3rd course, we were starting to get pretty full. I was barely able to to finish my 5th course along with the small desserts that were given to us. We didn't have to go to In-n-Out after all! The portion sizes here are decent sizes. If you plan to pick the 5 course option, make sure you come on a completely empty stomach! Now I can cross this one Michelin star restaurant off my food bucket list!

Review #338 - 2019 If you asked me what I wanted for my 30th birthday, I would most definitely say a brand name handbag... But being in my 40's, my priorities in life has most definitely changed. Now, I prefer to spend that money on things that I can enjoy with my family. Gary Danko's has been under the radar for me for a long while, but I've never had the guts to try it since everyone on Yelp makes such rude remarks about people who bring babies/toddlers to high end dining atmospheres. However, for me, I love my child so I want to bring her everywhere with me & if I can afford it, who are they to tell me that I can't when the restaurant isn't stopping me?? Fast forward to mid November when I finally sucked it up and tried to make reservations for my birthday weekend, not really expecting there to be any availability since I was cutting it quite close and GD takes their reservations two months out in advance. I got lucky and landed a reservation for Saturday, December 7th, at 9 PM. Although, it was a little late, but my family's a night owl so we didn't mind it. When the day finally came, I was actually happy that our dinner was so late since it was raining the majority of the day & it finally stopped right before our dinner. I had my 10-year old niece with me so I had to call the restaurant to see if they were willing to accommodate an extra person in our party & they told us it was no problem since the 4th person in our party is my 3-year old. We were seated immediately upon our arrival. We lucked out & got a booth which seated all five of us perfectly. However, we did get a lot of weird looks since everyone in the place were over 25 years old & we're here with three kids. Luckily, my kids are pretty well behaved so we didn't have any issue throughout our 3-hour meal, which was pretty unexpected since I'm used to restaurants trying to push us out so they can seat the next group. We all decided on a 4-course meal, but I think we could've done a 3-course and be perfectly happy since everyone was suffering at the end of the meal from over eating and we still ended up with left overs to take home. We started off with their complimentary amuse bouche, which is the Thai coconut milk soup. I'm from Thailand & I normally don't care for coconut milk soup, but they did a good job recreating this broth. My daughter & I both had an order of the seafood risotto, which was good & very filling. I think I already got full from just this first course. My husband had the glazed oyster with osetra caviar, which was very good. I'm not a big fan of oysters, but this dish was a very nice touch. My son had the seared ahi tuna with avocado, which he really enjoyed, but he still wished that he had gotten the glazed oysters instead. My son & I both ordered the loin of lamb, which I thought was just ok. I've had better, but it was still well made. I also had the lemon pepper duck breast with duck hash, which was good, but I was already stuffed by this time. My husband had the seared filet of beef, which he enjoyed. We decided to order the pork tenderloin & confit pork belly for my niece, but she doesn't eat meat for some strange reason so we ended up sharing her dish amongst the three of us & we all agreed that it was our favorite out of all the main entrees. My son & my niece had the cheese plate as their third course and they just left it to the server to pick their cheeses and they seemed quite happy with the selections. My husband had the salmon medallion, which was pretty good, but we felt that the horseradish was very overwhelming. For dessert, my son & I went with the chocolate soufflé, but my daughter ended up eating about 70% of it so I was thankful that the restaurant gave me 2 complimentary birthday desserts, which I didn't really eat much of. The key lime mousse was good, but I'm not the biggest fan of lime flavored anything so I pushed it off to my husband. Luckily, he ordered the trio crème brûlée, which I ended up stealing the original and left him with the bourbon & banana walnut, I think. My niece attacked her crème fraîche cheesecake without having to be told so I guess it was that good! Although, she didn't touch any of the kiwi bits. Overall, we'll definitely come back for the food, but next time we know exactly what we really liked from this experience. Service was top notch from start to finish. Every single staff member was friendly, accommodating & polite. They never made us feel uncomfortable about bringing our kids. They actually gave us extra attention because of the kids. We went back home with some complimentary pineapple breakfast cake, as well. Thank you GD staff members for making my 41st birthday meal a very enjoyable & memorable experience! We'll definitely be back!

    I wish I was blown away by Gary Danko, I really do.

    My company hosted a dinner here and I'm not usually one for uptight upscale restaurants but in the holiday spirit I was up for it, and plus if it's on the company tab why not?

    They saved us a room upstairs. It was intimate and the room smelled lovely. The fresh flowers were a romantic touch.

    We each chose the three course option. I opted for the rock shrimp risotto, the lobster, and the filet.

    They start out by giving you slivers of bread and butter. If I could eat one thing forever it would be bread and butter and it's always been my weakness. For Valentine's Day I think it's much more romantic and practical to get your lover a loaf of quality bread than flowers that she could never eat. The bread here is tasty! And the servers are like AI robots and understand when your plate is empty and they keep comin with their yield and oh is it fruitful.

    The evening started off with a small bowl of mushroom soup, or what I prefer to it as mushroom essence. The portion was made for ants.

    The rock shrimp risotto was how I would imagine it to be--creamy and filling but somehow a tad delicate with the lightly crunchy rock shrimp bits. This by itself was filling on its own and whatever dairy they put in really made me bloated. Delicious nonetheless!

    The rockstar highlight of my night was probably their lobster dish. I don't eat lobster often because I prefer the flavor of crab but this lobster was buttery, soft yet had undertones of crunchiness, and was just decadent. I could eat ten plates of this if they let me and if my cholesterol would be kind to me.

    The star of the show was supposed to be the filet with the blue cheese, however I was underwhelmed as this was said to be one of their more popular dishes. I'm a fan of steak and think it's a good baseline dish to compare restaurants however this one was my least favorite. The steak didn't have a steak like flavor but was instead masked by the strong aroma and presence of an sweltering deep onion base. The whole night I was burping pure sweated onion flavor. I think I could have done without the sauce at the bottom and just ate the steak dry with the potato bits. For such a quality cut of meat I felt like it was ruined by the overwhelming scent of onion that it felt as though I ate onion flesh.

    You technically don't have to order dessert as they bring out mini bite sized pieces of fun at the end.

    The lobster was definitely the highlight. The customer service was good in the fact that they were attentive and each waiter came out in line order as if they were marching to set your plate. They could crack a smile lol but I guess that's the appeal of a serious place like this. Overall I would say the food was not memorable enough for me or didn't feel special as I thought it would.

    I started off the new year by dining at one Michelin star restaurant. My boyfriend and I decided to go with the 5 course meal because we haven't eaten much since lunch time. We said that if we were still hungry after our 5 courses, we would walk over to In-n-Out for more food haha.

One of the staff gave me a table bag hook to hang my bag. This is actually a really genius idea! I have this item at home too, but I forgot to bring it. We were given the drink and food menus as well as tap water and a complimentary small sweet carrot soup (?). I couldn't remember what our waitress said that the soup was, but it was delicious. We were also served complimentary bread and butter. WARNING: DO NOT FILL UP ON BREAD. This is a dangerous idea! I always tell myself not to eat too much bread even though I love bread. I can tell you that eating 3 slices of bread was definitely a bad idea for me!

    FOOD:
    *Risotto with Rock Shrimp, Dungeness Crab, Celery Root and White Beech Mushrooms (5/5) - Top 2 favorite. I love rice and cheese. This dish didn't feel too heavy. The crab was definitely a nice touch to this dish!
    *Seared Striped Bass with Petite Thai Salad, Broccoli Rabe and Satay Sauce (3.5/5) - I enjoyed the seared bass, but I wasn't too fund of the salad. I don't like minced veggies as much. The flavor was just okay.
    *Lemon Pepper Duck Breast with Duck Hash, Celeriac-Garlic Purée, Belgain Endive and Cardamom Poached Pears (5/5) - I really enjoyed the duck breast and duck hash. I've never had duck hash before, so this was very interesting to try.
    *Pork Tenderloin with Confit Pork Belly, Brussels Sprouts, Chestnuts, Butternut Squash, Apples and Raisin-Pine Nut Relish (5/5) - Top 2 favorite. This dish had a good balance of meat and delicious veggies.
    *Grand Marnier Soufflé with Orange Sauce and Blood Orange Sorbet (4/5) - I really enjoyed the souffle, but the orange sauce was WAY TOO SWEET. If you compare this to milk tea, I would say that the sugar level is like at least 200%! I couldn't eat the orange sauce anymore, so I just finished the souffle and the sorbet instead.

    Towards the end of our 5 courses, we were given a plate of small bite size desserts to eat with our main desserts as well. We were also given complimentary breakfast treats!

    SERVICE (5/5): The staff was friendly, professional, and very attentive! We were constantly getting water refills and bread refills. Whenever we finished a course, the staff would quickly clear our table and provide us with a new pair of silverware. We were constantly being asked if the food was okay. Whenever we stepped away from our seat to use the restroom, the staff would fold our handkerchiefs and place it back on the table. Once you're done eating and paying for your food, they will ask if you had your car valeted or if you want them to call a taxi to get you a ride home. Very excellent service!

    OVERALL EXPERIENCE:
    We had a wonderful dining experience here. The food was good, but it wasn't as spectacular/hyped as I thought it would be. IMO, there are non-Michelin star restaurants that have more amazing food than this restaurant. I must say, we definitely misjudged out appetites. After our 3rd course, we were starting to get pretty full. I was barely able to to finish my 5th course along with the small desserts that were given to us. We didn't have to go to In-n-Out after all! The portion sizes here are decent sizes. If you plan to pick the 5 course option, make sure you come on a completely empty stomach! Now I can cross this one Michelin star restaurant off my food bucket list!

    If you asked me what I wanted for my 30th birthday, I would most definitely say a brand name handbag...

    But being in my 40's, my priorities in life has most definitely changed.  Now, I prefer to spend that money on things that I can enjoy with my family.

    Gary Danko's has been under the radar for me for a long while, but I've never had the guts to try it since everyone on Yelp makes such rude remarks about people who bring babies/toddlers to high end dining atmospheres.  

    However, for me, I love my child so I want to bring her everywhere with me & if I can afford it, who are they to tell me that I can't when the restaurant isn't stopping me??

    Fast forward to mid November when I finally sucked it up and tried to make reservations for my birthday weekend, not really expecting there to be any availability since I was cutting it quite close and GD takes their reservations two months out in advance.

    I got lucky and landed a reservation for Saturday, December 7th, at 9 PM.  Although, it was a little late, but my family's a night owl so we didn't mind it.

    When the day finally came, I was actually happy that our dinner was so late since it was raining the majority of the day & it finally stopped right before our dinner.

    I had my 10-year old niece with me so I had to call the restaurant to see if they were willing to accommodate an extra person in our party & they told us it was no problem since the 4th person in our party is my 3-year old.

    We were seated immediately upon our arrival.  We lucked out & got a booth which seated all five of us perfectly.  However, we did get a lot of weird looks since everyone in the place were over 25 years old & we're here with three kids.

    Luckily, my kids are pretty well behaved so we didn't have any issue throughout our 3-hour meal, which was pretty unexpected since I'm used to restaurants trying to push us out so they can seat the next group.

    We all decided on a 4-course meal, but I think we could've done a 3-course and be perfectly happy since everyone was suffering at the end of the meal from over eating and we still ended up with left overs to take home.

    We started off with their complimentary amuse bouche, which is the Thai coconut milk soup.  I'm from Thailand & I normally don't care for coconut milk soup, but they did a good job recreating this broth.

    My daughter & I both had an order of the seafood risotto, which was good & very filling.  I think I already got full from just this first course.

    My husband had the glazed oyster with osetra caviar, which was very good.  I'm not a big fan of oysters, but this dish was a very nice touch.

    My son had the seared ahi tuna with avocado, which he really enjoyed, but he still wished that he had gotten the glazed oysters instead.

    My son & I both ordered the loin of lamb, which I thought was just ok.  I've had better, but it was still well made.

    I also had the lemon pepper duck breast with duck hash, which was good, but I was already stuffed by this time.

    My husband had the seared filet of beef, which he enjoyed.

    We decided to order the pork tenderloin & confit pork belly for my niece, but she doesn't eat meat for some strange reason so we ended up sharing her dish amongst the three of us & we all agreed that it was our favorite out of all the main entrees.

    My son & my niece had the cheese plate as their third course and they just left it to the server to pick  their cheeses and they seemed quite happy with the selections.

    My husband had the salmon medallion, which was pretty good, but we felt that the horseradish was very overwhelming.

    For dessert, my son & I went with the chocolate soufflé, but my daughter ended up eating about 70% of it so I was thankful that the restaurant gave me 2 complimentary birthday desserts, which I didn't really eat much of.

    The key lime mousse was good, but I'm not the biggest fan of lime flavored anything so I pushed it off to my husband.  Luckily, he ordered the trio crème brûlée, which I ended up stealing the original and left him with the bourbon & banana walnut, I think.

    My niece attacked her crème fraîche cheesecake without having to be told so I guess it was that good!  Although, she didn't touch any of the kiwi bits.

    Overall, we'll definitely come back for the food, but next time we know exactly what we really liked from this experience.

    Service was top notch from start to finish.  Every single staff member was friendly, accommodating & polite.  They never made us feel uncomfortable about bringing our kids.  They actually gave us extra attention because of the kids.

    We went back home with some complimentary pineapple breakfast cake, as well.

    Thank you GD staff members for making my 41st birthday meal a very enjoyable & memorable experience!  We'll definitely be back!

    Embed review

    7/9/2019

    14 photos

    1 check-in

    The biggest takeaway that my party and I absolutely enjoyed, and were wowed was the synchronized harmony with the arrival of our courses at the same time. As a Michelin star restaurant, I expected nothing less and I was definitely impressed.

    This was my first visit to Restaurant Gary Danko and I absolutely loved the ambiance, service, and the food.

    There was a mixture of attire, however, none of which that came in t-shirts and shorts. I came in I suppose (casual trendy?); blazer, sweater, and corduroy pants. I did see one gentleman with a hooded sweatshirt. I suppose in this day in age, as long as your dressed appropriately, that you will not be turned away. I had dined at Brennan's in New Orleans, and there were people in yoga pants, shorts, sleeveless shirts; at the least they payed, but made it seem less high end.  

    Ambiance: dimly lit for a romantic setting, which was also cozy as I generally like low lit settings. The overall design was modern and well appointed. It reminded me of how Wynn designs their resorts, minus floral carpeting and Chinese decorations. The Wynn style that is reminiscent is the placement of large golden vases and floral arrangements.

    Service: the night was very well staffed, as each one assisted with getting food out each at the same time, pouring water when glasses were not full, and of course the waiter that would provide recommendations and take orders. Service was perfect. I am somewhat of a klutz when I eat, and I try not to do, on the rare occasions I do end up with food on my shirt. A waiter handed me a packet of Shout Instant Laundry Wipe; how thoughtful!

    Alcohol: I started with The Crowed Pleaser (a rum based drink, which I absolutely love rum), and ended with an Old Fashioned. The two other guests in my party opted for Old Fashioned's, and Martini / Cosmopolitan.

    Food: the menu itself seemed endless, however our waiter Dennis assured us that there is no wrong way of ordering and you can mix and match to our hearts desire. We opted for the 4 course menu priced at $113, and each chose 1 appetizer, 1 main fish course, 1 main meat course, and 1 dessert. We each ordered cocktails to go alongside the food. Come hungry, because you will leave full.

    A small cup sized of chilled squash soup was complimentary of the house; citrus-y and a great palette cleanser.

    Appetizers: Dungeness Crab Melon Salad, Seared Ahi Tuna & Risotto With Rock Shrimp.

    Fish Main Course: Seared Sea Scallops, Seared Stripe Bass & Roasted Maine Lobster.

    Meat Main Course: Mousseline Pork Tenderloin With Pork Belly, Lemon Pepper Duck Breast & Seared Filet of Beef.

    Dessert: Rhubarb Tart, Lemon Souffle Pannacotta Cake & Louisiana Butter Cake.

    Extra: a platter of miniature desserts were served at the end.

    It was also a birthday for 1 in my party, and they brought out a Lemon Sorbet cake out to help celebrate.

    I am not going to elaborate completely on how the food tasted, as it would be a bit much to describe. But, I will say that everything was delicious and you cannot go wrong with any of the dishes.

    Raspberry Breakfast Cakes, wrapped in gold foil and tied with black lace were given at the end of everything; of which I enjoyed the next day as a snack.

    Will definitely come again!

    See all photos from Alex C. for Gary Danko
